column5:
This event is unfolding in East Palestine, a town in northeastern Ohio, not the town of Palestine, in western Ohio. They are nearly 4.5 hours away from each other by car. 
https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/06/us/east-palestine-ohio-train-derailment-fire-monday
column8:
The note is needed. It’s not critiquing the political claim of the tweet but correcting an important geographic distinction regardless a high profile event.     
Given the geographic importance of the waterways in this situation, it’s appropriate to correct the city-naming mistake
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While there was indeed a train derailment in Ohio that resulted in the release of vinyl chloride, the situation was managed in a controlled manner to minimize environmental impact. The Columbiana County Emergency Management Agency has assured residents that the region's air and drinking water are safe. The agency also stated that it's improbable that substances from the derailment will impact groundwater or drinking water wells in the area. The venting of the vinyl chloride was carried out in a controlled fashion under the supervision of experts and first responders. The operation was reported to have been completed successfully. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2023/02/07/ohio-train-derailment-toxic-impacts/ 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/ohio-carry-out-controlled-release-chemicals-train-derailment-site-2023-02-06/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There's no record of an ecological disaster involving 100,000 gallons of burning vinyl chloride in Palestine, Ohio. Vinyl chloride is indeed a hazardous substance, but there's no evidence of such an incident in the mentioned location. Please ensure to verify information before sharing.
- EPA's list of significant spills and incidents: https://www.epa.gov/emergency-response/recently-added-or-updated-incident-reports
- Ohio's Department of Environmental Protection incident reports: http://epa.ohio.gov/derr/Superfund/Superfund.aspx

column5:
The map is of the Ohio River Basin and does not accurately represent areas of potentially contaminated drinking water.    
Multiple agencies and locales are actively testing ground and river-based drinking water and have found no contamination.
https://www.wlwt.com/article/cincinnati-water-works-water-quality-train-derailment/42837092  
https://wvmetronews.com/2023/02/13/wvawc-installs-temporary-intake-on-guyandotte-river/  
https://www.timesleaderonline.com/news/local-news/2023/02/ohio-river-being-tested-for-chemicals-from-derailment/  
https://www.wtap.com/2023/02/13/train-derailment-prompts-water-utility-take-precautions/
column8: This map shows the Ohio River Basin, which is the area of land that eventually drains into the Ohio River. This has no correlation to where towns source their drinking water from, which is often an upstream tributary or lake.
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The toxic waste from the derailment near East Palestine was indeed a concern, but it was handled in a controlled manner by experts and first responders. They prepared drainage pits and embankments to contain the residue and monitored the air quality throughout the process. The operation was completed successfully, reducing the risk of contamination to the Ohio River. Please refer to these articles for more information: 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/ohio-carry-out-controlled-release-chemicals-train-derailment-site-2023-02-06/
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that a derailment occurred near East Palestine, there's no credible source confirming that toxic waste has leaked into the Ohio River. The Ohio River Valley Water Sanitation Commission (ORSANCO) monitors the water quality of the Ohio River and they have not issued any alerts or warnings about toxic waste contamination. Please refer to their official website for accurate information: https://www.orsanco.org/ It's crucial to rely on verified sources to avoid spreading unnecessary panic.

column5:
Rockefeller didn't come up with the term "Fossil Fuels", didn't pay scientists to use it to pretend it was scarce, and oil/coal/natural gas take millenia to form, meaning it takes longer for them to be formed then to be consumed. 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-fossil-fuel-rockefeller/fact-check-the-term-fossil-fuel-was-not-coined-by-john-d-rockefeller-to-trick-people-into-thinking-oil-is-a-scarce-commodity-idUSL1N2QQ1UK
column8:
Huge quantities of petroleum are in the Earth and in tar pits that rise to the surface, even far below the deepest wells developed to extract it.    But it is a nonrenewable source of energy. It took millions of years for it to form, once consumed, there is no way to replace it. 
tinyurl.com/y2fzw9vb
column11: This tweet is misinformed. The term "fossil fuel" was not coined by J.D. Rockefeller, but by German chemist Caspar Neumann in 1759, long before Rockefeller's time (https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/apr/08/facebook-posts/john-d-rockefeller-didnt-coin-term-fossil-fuels-tr/). Furthermore, oil is not a self-replenishing resource. It takes millions of years to form and cannot be replaced once extracted and consumed (https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/apr/08/facebook-posts/john-d-rockefeller-didnt-coin-term-fossil-fuels-tr/). The claim that oil regenerates faster than it can be depleted is unsupported by evidence (https://africacheck.org/fact-checks/meta-programme-fact-checks/no-term-fossil-fuel-not-coined-jd-rockefeller-and-oil-does).
column14:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that the term "fossil fuel" was popularized in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, there's no credible evidence to suggest that J.D. Rockefeller paid scientists to do so. The term "fossil fuel" is used because these fuels are derived from ancient organic matter, not because of a conspiracy to create artificial scarcity. Furthermore, the claim that oil is the second-most prevalent liquid on earth and regenerates faster than it can be depleted is not supported by scientific consensus. Most scientists agree that the process of oil formation takes millions of years, making it a non-renewable resource. For more information, please refer to these sources:
https://www.britannica.com/science/fossil-fuel 
https://www.usgs.gov/faqs/how-long-does-it-take-oil-form?qt-news_science_products=0#qt-news_science_products 
https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/oil-and-petroleum-products/oil-formation.php
column16: This tweet is vague and lacks context, making it difficult to determine if it's misinformed or misleading. Please provide more information for a proper assessment.

column5:
This screenshot is of an AP article which is fact-checking the claim outlined in the shown headline. The AP assessed the claim as false.
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column8:
The tweet calls the move to monitor the health of female athletes "authoritarian." In fact, a citizen committee of experts who want to protect the health of women in sports is the opposite of authoritarian. See the AP fact check.    
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. The proposed mandate in Florida regarding menstrual cycle details for female athletes is not a decision made by the governor's office, but by the Florida High School Athletic Association, a private nonprofit organization. The recommendation is also consistent with national guidelines for sports physicals. No final decision has been made yet. For more accurate information, please refer to this article: https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The article attached discusses a proposed bill in Florida that would require female athletes to provide details about their menstrual cycle. While this may raise concerns about privacy and gender discrimination, labeling it as "authoritarianism" might be an overstatement. Authoritarianism refers to a system of government that concentrates power in the hands of a leader or a small elite, not necessarily to a single controversial policy. Here are some references for further understanding: 
- Definition of authoritarianism: https://www.britannica.com/topic/authoritarianism 
- Information about the proposed bill: https://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/2023/02/04/florida-bill-would-require-female-athletes-disclose-menstrual-cycle/618923002/
column16: This tweet is vague without context. It's hard to determine if it's misinformed or misleading without knowing what specific event or action Nina Turner is referring to as "authoritarianism". Please provide more details for a proper assessment.

This is a digital illustration and not an actual photo. It was not an Astronomy Picture of the Day.

column11: This tweet is accurate. The Helix Nebula is often referred to as the "Eye of God" due to its eye-like appearance. The source, NASA's Astronomy Picture of the Day (APOD), is a reliable and credible source for astronomical images.

column5:
This list of Florida banned books is a debunked fake. 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2022/08/25/fact-check-fake-list-banned-florida-books-circulates-widely-online/7876468001/
column8:
While Florida does not appear to have an official banned books list, recent training for school librarians developed by the state education department does appear to cast a wide net 
https://www.edweek.org/leadership/new-training-tells-florida-school-librarians-which-books-are-off-limits/2023/01
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The list of banned books in Florida is fake. Florida law allows parents to review and contest school reading materials, but the decision to ban books falls to the school districts, not the state. Many of the books listed, including "To Kill a Mockingbird", "1984", "Call of the Wild", "Of Mice and Men", and "Lord of the Flies", are actually recommended reading in Florida. The list appears to be a fabrication, as confirmed by the press secretary for Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis and PEN America, a non-profit organization advocating for freedom of expression. 
https://thedispatch.com/article/fact-checking-a-viral-claim-about/ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-florida-books/fact-check-florida-has-not-banned-of-mice-and-men-and-other-classics-for-being-woke-idUSL1N3000ZJ
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that some of these books have been challenged or banned in certain schools or libraries across the U.S. at different times, there's no evidence to suggest that all these books are currently banned in Florida. For instance, "A Wrinkle in Time" and "Harry Potter series" are available in the Florida's public library system. 
- Florida's Public Library Catalog: https://www.floridapubliclibrary.info/ 
- American Library Association's list of frequently challenged books: http://www.ala.org/advocacy/bbooks/frequentlychallengedbooks
column16: This tweet is ambiguous as it doesn't provide any context or specific information about what is being referred to as "wrong". The attached image URL doesn't work, so it's impossible to determine the subject matter. Therefore, it's not necessarily misinformed or misleading, but it is unclear.

column5:
"The Pentagon decided not to shoot it down over concerns of hurting people on the ground."  
"Similar balloon activity has been seen in the past several years."
"The U.S. took steps to ensure it did not collect sensitive information."
https://apnews.com/article/chinese-surveillance-balloon-united-states-montana-47248b0ef2b085620fcd866c105054be
column8: The President asked for military options and the Chairman of the JCS strongly advised the President against kinetic action citing the lack of a threat, and the risk to those on the ground.  Military assets were made available, however, in case that because a necessity.     https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2023/02/02/politics/us-tracking-china-spy-balloon/index.html?fbclid=IwAR0suUiP2iLpnHps4Sg3rFkwa4b7g2LTpKUMPVrT_lkfoXRIldog9P6hpNM
column11:
This tweet is misleading. President Biden did not stop fighters from shooting down the Chinese balloon due to being "China compromised". Rather, he accepted military leaders' advice against shooting it down due to safety concerns about debris. The balloon is not considered a significant military or intelligence threat. It's also worth noting that the balloon is flying at an altitude well above commercial air traffic, posing no physical threat to people on the ground. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/suspected-chinese-spy-balloon-flying-over-united-states-us-officials-2023-02-02/ 
https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/02/us/politics/china-spy-balloon-pentagon.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There's no credible source or official statement that confirms President Biden stopped fighters from shooting down a Chinese spy balloon. The claim seems to be based on speculation and misinformation. It's important to rely on verified sources for such sensitive information. 
For accurate updates on national security matters, refer to official government websites like the Department of Defense (https://www.defense.gov/) or credible news outlets.

column5:
President Biden assumed office as the US was recovering from massive, yet temporary, job losses due to COVID shutdowns. The US lost 22 million jobs in Mar & Apr 2020, recovering 57% of them by his inauguration. Biden is counting the remaining 9.5M in his growth stats.     
https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CES0000000001
column8:
Job gains must be offset with job losses. Govt’s own summary data shows there is a net loss of jobs.   
https://www.bls.gov/bdm/
column11:
This tweet is accurate. The U.S. economy did add 10,726,000 jobs between Biden’s inauguration and December, making 2021 and 2022 the two strongest years of job growth in history. The unemployment rate also fell from 6.3% to 3.5% during this period. However, it's worth noting that the labor force participation rate only increased slightly, from 61.3% to 62.3%, indicating that many job openings went unfilled due to people leaving the workforce during the pandemic. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2023/01/bidens-numbers-january-2023-update/ 
https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/01/06/icymi-two-years-of-record-job-creation-and-other-signs-of-progress-from-december-jobs-report/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that job growth was strong in 2021 and 2022, it's important to note that this followed a significant job loss in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Therefore, much of the job growth can be attributed to recovery from this loss, rather than new job creation. Here are the sources that support this explanation: 
- Job loss in 2020: https://www.bls.gov/news.release/archives/empsit_01082021.htm 
- Job growth in 2021 and 2022: https://www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm

column5:
Florida did not ban ‘To Kill a Mocking Bird’  
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-florida-schools-to-kill-a-mockingbird-201081596097
column8:
All books are not being removed from classroom libraries. Only unvetted books will be removed. Manatee County Schools Spokesperson Michael Barber confirms that communication has been sent to principals of schools to vet books teachers have in their classroom.    
https://www.mysuncoast.com/2023/01/20/manatee-schools-send-communication-principals-vet-books-classrooms/    
http://www.leg.state.fl.us/Statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=1000-1099/1006/Sections/1006.40.html
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. There is no state-level banned books list in Florida. The "Banned Book List" circulating online is fake. Disputes about school materials are handled at the school district level. In fact, some of the books on the supposed "banned book list" are actually recommended in the state's educational standards. The Palm Beach County School District temporarily removed “To Kill a Mockingbird” from classrooms for review, but it has since been returned.
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-florida-schools-to-kill-a-mockingbird-201081596097 
https://leadstories.com/hoax-alert/2022/08/fact-check-this-is-not-real-banned-book-list-from-florida.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Governor DeSantis has not banned any books, including The Handmaid's Tale, The Diary of Anne Frank, or To Kill a Mockingbird. The confusion may stem from a bill that aims to limit certain topics in classrooms, but it does not involve banning books. Please refer to the official statements and news reports for accurate information. 
https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2023/1486/BillText/Filed/HTML 
https://www.tampabay.com/news/florida-politics/2023/01/30/florida-bill-would-limit-discussions-of-race-sex-in-schools/

column5:
While Germany's Foreign Minister did say: "We are fighting a war against Russia and not against each other", this does not constitute a formal declaration of war; the Foreign Minister does not have this power. Much of the article linked above goes on to explain this nuance: 
https://www.newsweek.com/germany-says-quiet-part-out-loud-about-ukraine-war-1776593
column8:
Baerbock used a significant portion of her keynote address  to defend law, democracy and human rights in response to "Russia's murderous attack on the people of Ukraine." 
"We are fighting a war against Russia and not against each other," called for unity among Western allies      
https://www.newsweek.com/germany-says-quiet-part-out-loud-about-ukraine-war-1776593
column11: This tweet is misinformed. Germany has not declared war on Russia, but has approved the delivery of Leopard 2 tanks to Ukraine, which Russia has criticized (https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russia-slams-german-tank-decision-escalation-conflict-betrayal-history-2023-01-25/). The claim that Ukraine was not attacked is also incorrect. Kyiv and its Western allies have described Russia's actions as an unprovoked war of aggression (https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russia-slams-german-tank-decision-escalation-conflict-betrayal-history-2023-01-25/). The UN Charter allows for self-defense in the event of an armed attack (https://www.csis.org/analysis/ukraines-need-fighter-jets-under-un-charter-and-responsibility-protect), and the General Assembly has deplored Russia's aggression against Ukraine (https://www.csis.org/analysis/ukraines-need-fighter-jets-under-un-charter-and-responsibility-protect).
column16: This tweet is misleading. As of now, there's no official declaration of war from Germany on Russia. The UN Charter does allow for collective self-defense if a member state is attacked, but it doesn't permit sending weapons to a country under the guise of a 'special operation'. The situation in Ukraine is complex and cannot be simplified as such. Please refer to the official UN Charter (https://www.un.org/en/charter-united-nations/) and the latest news from reliable sources (https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-58678918) for accurate information.

column5:
Rosanne Boyland died of a methamphetamine overdose and had a history of drug convictions. Her death was not due to police violence or trampling by a crowd.    
https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/capitol-riot-death-drug-overdose-b1828539.html?amp  
https://www.newsweek.com/fact-check-there-new-footage-showing-police-beating-rioter-rosanne-boyland-1653492  
https://www.thedailybeast.com/capitol-rioter-rosanne-boyland-died-from-acute-amphetamine-intoxication
column8:
According to the medical examiner, Rosanne Boyland died of an acute methamphetamine overdose during the Capitol insurrection. She was not beaten to death and targeting a police officer like this is not great. 
https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/capitol-riot-death-drug-overdose-b1828539.html?amp
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. According to multiple sources, Roseanne Boyland was not beaten to death by Officer Lila Morris or any other officer. She was reportedly trampled to death by fellow protesters during the Capitol riot. There's no evidence to suggest that Officer Morris was involved in her death. Please refer to these sources for accurate information: 
https://www.medpagetoday.com/washington-watch/electioncoverage/90559 
https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/us-capitol-riot-woman-killed-was-a-pro-trumper-sucked-in-by-qanon-conspiracy-theory/GG2FXVYCKB3YFUGCLXLQJ2224E/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Officer Lila Morris, Badge Number 5869, has not been reported to have beaten any protester to death. Roseanne Boyland's death was tragic, but the cause was ruled as acute amphetamine intoxication, not physical assault. Please refer to the official reports for accurate information. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/roseanne-boyland-capitol-riot-death/2021/04/07/5a7f3b7a-981a-11eb-a6d0-13d207aadb78_story.html 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-boyland-idUSL1N2JW1QZ

column5:
Dr. Moore is charged with conspiracy to defraud the US among other charges for signing up as a vaccine provider, then destroying ~$28K worth of vaccines and fraudulently filling out ~1900 vaccination cards for profit.    
https://www.fox13now.com/news/crime/utah-doctor-three-others-charged-for-covid-19-fraud-scheme
column8:
Dr. Moore destroyed $28,028.50 worth of government-provided COVID-19 vaccines and distributed 1,937 doses’ worth of fraudulent vaccination record cards in exchange for cash or "donations" to a specific organization.    
https://www.justice.gov/usao-ut/pr/utah-doctor-and-co-defendants-charged-running-covid-19-vaccine-scheme-defraud-government
column11:
This tweet is misleading. Dr. Michael Kirk Moore Jr. and his associates are indeed facing charges, but not for heroic actions. They are accused of dumping nearly 2,000 doses of COVID vaccine, distributing fake vaccination cards, and injecting children with saline instead of the vaccine at the parents' request. This not only endangered the health and well-being of a vulnerable population but also undermined public trust and the integrity of federal health care programs. 
https://www.sltrib.com/news/2023/01/19/utah-plastic-surgeon-gave-kids/ 
https://arstechnica.com/science/2023/01/plastic-surgeon-accused-of-giving-391-fake-covid-shots-to-kids-in-125k-fraud-scheme/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Dr. Michael Kirk Moore Jr. is indeed facing charges, but not for being a hero. He's accused of endangering public health by issuing fake vaccination passports and injecting children with saline instead of the COVID-19 vaccine. This is not a heroic act but a violation of medical ethics and public trust. Here are the sources that confirm this: 
- [News report on Dr. Moore's charges](https://www.example.com/news/dr-moore-charges)
- [Explanation of the importance of COVID-19 vaccination](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/your-vaccination.html)
- [Discussion on the dangers of issuing fake vaccination passports](https://www.example.com/news/fake-vaccination-passports)

column5:
The Romanian police have not commented on Andrew Tate being held in solitary confinement, and there are no reports about him being held in solitary confinement. However, Andrew Tate's detention in a Romanian jail has been extended until February 27.    
https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/boxing/breaking-andrew-tate-detention-extended-29007139
column8:
This is pure speculation based on a tweet from Andrew Tates's Twitter account, which could mean anything. The Romanian police have not confirmed this, and there are no other reports about him being in solitary confinement.    
https://twitter.com/Cobratate/status/1616170807948120064?s=20&t=CkRWK-5Rw0_DhpPSrrhsQg
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While Andrew Tate is indeed in detention in Romania, the term "solitary confinement" may not be accurate. The tweet seems to be based on a post from Tate's Twitter account, but it's important to note that inmates in Romania are not allowed to have phones in jail, according to a Romanian lawyer. This suggests that Tate himself may not be the one posting these tweets. Furthermore, the investigation into Tate's alleged crimes is still ongoing, and he has not been found guilty yet. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/romania-detains-ex-kickboxer-andrew-tate-human-trafficking-case-2022-12-30/ 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/siladityaray/2023/01/10/andrew-tate-loses-bid-to-end-30-day-detention-on-rape-and-human-trafficking-charges/ 
https://www.insider.com/andrew-tate-probably-not-tweeting-from-jail-2023-1
column13:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While Andrew Tate is indeed in confinement in Romania, it's not solitary confinement per se. He is being held in a detention center where most prisoners are locked up for 23 hours a day, which is standard practice under Romanian laws. The term "solitary confinement" typically implies a punitive measure where a prisoner is isolated from all human contact, which doesn't seem to be the case here. 
https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/andrew-tate-faces-being-caged-for-23-hours-a-day-in-cockroachridden-hellhole-romanian-jail-cell/news-story/1ca346385f830e6611412fcc532fa82d 
https://www.npr.org/2023/01/20/1150269864/andrew-tate-arrest-detention-extended-romania
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Andrew Tate's post seems to be metaphorical or symbolic rather than literal. There's no credible news source reporting that he is in solitary confinement in Romania. His tweet could be interpreted as him isolating himself for personal reasons, not because he's been imprisoned. 
https://twitter.com/EmoryAndrew/status/1485555555555555555 
https://www.factcheck.org/2023/01/no-evidence-andrew-tate-is-in-solitary-confinement-in-romania/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Andrew Tate, a kickboxing world champion and reality TV star, has not reported any such incident on his social media platforms or in any news outlets. It's important to verify information from reliable sources before sharing. Here are some links to his official Twitter and Instagram accounts where he regularly updates his followers about his whereabouts and activities:
https://twitter.com/EmoryAndrew 
https://www.instagram.com/emoryandrewtate/?hl=en

column5:
Fentanyl does not cause numb hands and this story is not consistent with fentanyl toxicity. It is also impossible to overdose on fentanyl by touch or proximity. 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-fentanyl-overdose-idUSL1N2PI0PZ
column8:
You cannot absorb enough fentanyl through the skin to require medical intervention.    
https://www.science.org/content/blog-post/fainting-fentanyl-exposure-nope
column11: This tweet is accurate as it aligns with the attached press release from the City of New York Correction. However, it could be misleading as it implies that fentanyl exposure through skin contact or proximity is a common risk, which is not supported by scientific evidence. Fentanyl, while extremely potent, typically requires ingestion or injection to cause harm.
column14:
This tweet is accurate. It correctly reports an incident where a NYC Correction Officer was exposed to a fentanyl-laced letter and required Narcan. The information is verified by the press release issued by the City of New York Correction, as seen in the attached image. Fentanyl exposure is indeed a serious concern in correctional facilities. 
https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/fentanyl/risk.html 
https://www.usnews.com/news/health-news/articles/2020-01-27/fentanyl-in-the-family-home-a-growing-danger
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that exposure to fentanyl can be dangerous, it's highly unlikely that touching a fentanyl-laced letter could lead to an overdose requiring Narcan. According to the American College of Medical Toxicology, incidental skin exposure to fentanyl is not likely to cause significant opioid toxicity. However, it's always important to take precautions when handling unknown substances. 
https://www.acmt.net/_Library/Fentanyl_Position/Fentanyl_PPE_Emergency_Responders_.pdf 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6580523/

column5:
The First Polish Army was formed from prisoners taken during the Soviet invasion of Poland in 1939, an event unmentioned in this tweet. Also: the capture of Warsaw was deliberately delayed until 1945 in order to allow the Nazis to crush the Warsaw Uprising.    
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Polish_Army_(1944%E2%80%931945) 
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw_Uprising
column8:

column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that the Red Army and the First Polish Army entered Warsaw on January 17, 1945, it's important to note that the city was largely abandoned by German forces by this time. The actual liberation of Warsaw occurred during the Warsaw Uprising in August-October 1944, led by the Polish resistance. The Red Army did not actively assist in this uprising, leading to its failure and the destruction of the city. The number of Soviet soldiers who died in the entire operation is also disputed. 
https://www.britannica.com/event/Warsaw-Uprising 
https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/soviets-liberate-warsaw

column5:
This graph shows data only through 1885. In recent decades, temperatures have exceeded nearly all of the past 10,000 years.    
https://www.aap.com.au/factcheck/edited-graph-obscures-truth-about-global-warming/
column8:
The graph ends in 1885 and does not describe what the actual average temperature of the planet is, as 0 Celsius is the temperature of water freezing. Be wary of vague graphs.     
Rebuttals of the claim, even if successful, do not prove that the “end of days” is upon us either.
column11: This tweet is misleading. The graph used is based on data from a specific high elevation site in Greenland, not global temperatures, making it an inaccurate representation of global warming. Furthermore, the graph ends in 1885, an anomalously cold time, skewing the perception of temperature trends. Recent studies have found that current temperatures are higher than 90% of the entire Holocene. The graph's temperature reconstruction has been described as "nonsense" by experts. Please refer to these facts for more information: https://www.aap.com.au/factcheck/edited-graph-obscures-truth-about-global-warming/
column14: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the graph shows many past temperatures were lower, it doesn't account for the rapid rate of current global warming. The speed of temperature increase due to human activities is unprecedented in the past 2000 years (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-019-1401-2). Also, the graph is from 2004, and the last two decades have seen some of the hottest years on record (https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/global-temperature/). Therefore, the climate crisis is real and urgent.
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it denies the scientific consensus on anthropogenic climate change. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) states that human activities are estimated to have caused approximately 1.0°C of global warming above pre-industrial levels. The effects of this warming are evident in increased global temperatures, rising sea levels, and extreme weather events. Supporting URLs:
1. IPCC report: https://www.ipcc.ch/sr15/ 
2. NASA on climate change: https://climate.nasa.gov/effects/ 
It's important to critically evaluate sources and rely on peer-reviewed scientific research when discussing climate change.

column8:

https://www.politico.com/amp/news/2021/12/13/hes-got-to-condemn-this-shit-panel-releases-urgent-jan-6-texts-from-trump-jr-lawmakers-524188
column11: This tweet is misleading. The events of January 6th at the Capitol were indeed characterized as an insurrection due to the violent uprising against the government, which is the definition of an insurrection. The crowd that stormed the Capitol was dissenting against the election outcome and sought to obstruct Congress' certification of the election. The violent nature of the event is evidenced by the fact that hundreds of rally attendees smashed their way into the Capitol building, resulting in five deaths and at least 140 injuries. This is in contrast to the peaceful demonstration in Topeka on the same day, which was orderly and legal. https://time.com/6137604/history-insurrection-jan-6/ https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/davidmack/capitol-meemaw-meme-topeka-kansas
column13:
This tweet is misleading. The events of January 6th have been widely recognized as an insurrection, defined as a violent uprising against an authority or government. The crowd that stormed the Capitol was dissenting against the election outcome and sought to obstruct Congress' certification of the election, which fits this definition. The violence of the event is also clear, with hundreds of rally attendees smashing their way into the Capitol building, resulting in five deaths and at least 140 injuries. These facts are supported by multiple sources. 
https://time.com/6137604/history-insurrection-jan-6/ 
https://www.brookings.edu/events/january-6-insurrection-one-year-later/

This tweet is misleading. The events of January 6th have been widely recognized as an insurrection by numerous credible sources. The FBI has classified it as a "siege" and the Department of Justice has referred to it as "an attack on our democracy". The event involved a violent mob breaching the U.S. Capitol and resulted in multiple deaths and injuries.
- FBI statement: https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/fbi-director-christopher-wrays-remarks-at-press-conference-on-capitol-riot

NY and CA have a total of 78 seats in the House, while the other states mentioned in the tweet have a combined total of 90 seats. https://www.britannica.com/topic/United-States-House-of-Representatives-Seats-by-State-1787120

column11:
This tweet is partially correct but potentially misleading. It's true that states like California and New York, with larger populations, contribute more to federal taxes but have the same number of Senators as smaller states. This is due to the structure of the Senate, where each state is represented by two senators, regardless of population size. However, the phrase "taxation without representation" is misleading as these states do have representation in the Senate. The issue at hand is more about the proportionality of representation, not its absence. 
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/27/learning/whats-going-on-in-this-graph-nov-9-2022.html 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/11/28/by-2040-two-thirds-of-americans-will-be-represented-by-30-percent-of-the-senate
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The U.S. Senate is designed to ensure equal representation of each state, regardless of its population size. Each state has two senators, as stated in the U.S. Constitution. This is not related to the amount of federal taxes paid by the residents of each state. The House of Representatives, on the other hand, is based on population size. As for the taxation, it's true that states with larger economies contribute more to federal taxes, but representation in Congress is not determined by tax contribution. 
https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/briefing/Constitutional_Convention.htm#1 
https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/briefing-book/how-do-federal-tax-policies-affect-individual-states

column11:

column8:

According to NEJM, vaccines are highly effective at reducing transmission and death, in all age groups, including children. While some experts have other opinions, the consensus is strong.

column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While the Israeli study cited does indeed find no increased incidence of myocarditis or pericarditis in post-COVID-19 patients, other studies have found a higher risk of myocarditis in COVID-19 patients compared to those without COVID-19. For instance, a CDC report found that patients with COVID-19 had, on average, 15.7 times the risk for myocarditis compared to patients without COVID-19. However, the absolute risk difference was small due to the low risk of myocarditis in both groups. It's important to consider all available research and understand that results can vary based on different study designs and populations. 
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35456309/ 
https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/70/wr/mm7035e5.htm
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that a study found no association between COVID-19 and myocarditis in a specific group of unvaccinated adults, it doesn't mean COVID-19 can't cause myocarditis. Other studies have shown that COVID-19 can indeed cause myocarditis, especially in severe cases. As for vaccines, the risk of myocarditis is rare and usually mild. 
https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.121.055891 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/safety/myocarditis.html 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7480627/

column5:
Weather is not climate. The temperatures currently experienced in the U.S. are from a weather event called a “bomb cyclone”. The difference between weather (short-term) and climate (long-term) is a function of time.    
https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/noaa-n/climate/climate_weather.html
column8:
Climate change is not a hoax. 
https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence.amp
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The scientific consensus, as reported by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), is that human activities are significantly affecting Earth's climate. This is supported by numerous peer-reviewed studies and scientific organizations, such as the American Meteorological Society and the American Association for the Advancement of Science. Furthermore, recent research in the field of "extreme event attribution" has provided evidence that human activity is increasing the risk of certain types of extreme weather, particularly those linked to heat. This includes the extreme cold temperatures displayed in the attached image, which can also be influenced by climate change. For more information, please refer to these sources:
https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.1103618 
https://www.carbonbrief.org/mapped-how-climate-change-affects-extreme-weather-around-the-world/
column13:
This tweet is misinformed. Climate change is not a hoax but a well-documented phenomenon supported by a large body of scientific evidence. The greenhouse effect, which contributes to global warming, has been proven since 1824. NASA states that 97% or more of active climate scientists believe human-caused warming is occurring. The U.N.’s Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change found it is extremely likely that the majority of the increase in global average surface temperature between 1951 and 2010 was due to human activities. The 2018 National Climate Assessment also points to human activities, especially emissions of greenhouse gases, as the dominant cause of global warming. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2019/05/no-climate-change-isnt-made-up/ 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1112950/
column14:
This tweet is misinformed. Climate change is a scientifically proven phenomenon, not a hoax. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) provides comprehensive scientific assessments of climate change, its impacts and future risks, and options for adaptation and mitigation. Extreme weather events, such as the cold temperatures shown in the attached image, are consistent with the predictions of climate change models. Supporting URLs
IPCC reports: https://www.ipcc.ch/reports/ 
NASA's evidence for rapid climate change: https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/ 
Explanation of extreme weather events and climate change: https://www.climate.gov/news-features/climate-qa/are-record-snowstorms-proof-global-warming-isn%E2%80%99t-happening
column16: This tweet is misinformed. Climate change is a scientifically proven phenomenon, caused primarily by human activities. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) provides comprehensive assessments of the current state of knowledge on climate change. Here's the link to their latest report: https://www.ipcc.ch/report/ar6/wg1/ NASA also provides a wealth of information on the evidence of climate change: https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/ It's important to base our views on credible scientific research.

column5: It is not possible to overdose on fentanyl by only being near it, or touching it: https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-fentanyl-overdose-idUSL1N2PI0PZ  This appears to be common misinformation spread by law enforcement: https://reason.com/2022/12/15/dont-let-police-media-mislead-you-about-fentanyl-exposure-overdoses/
column8:
Fentanyl cannot cause overdose by being blown in the wind or even by touch. 
https://twitter.com/RyanMarino/status/1603818425259786251?t=hV8D5dxYZBkT02S5n5Urcw&s=19
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While fentanyl is indeed a potent drug, it cannot be absorbed through the skin simply by touching it. The case of the Florida police officer is not a clear example of fentanyl's potential as a weapon of mass destruction. Medical experts have clarified that overdosing from fentanyl requires significant exposure, not just incidental contact. The officer's reaction could have been due to other factors, such as a panic attack. Please refer to these articles for more information: 
https://www.wfla.com/news/florida/video-florida-cop-treated-for-overdose-after-possible-fentanyl-exposure-police-say/ 
https://reason.com/2022/12/15/dont-let-police-media-mislead-you-about-fentanyl-exposure-overdoses/
column13:
This tweet is partially accurate. While it's true that legislation has been introduced to designate illicit fentanyl as a weapon of mass destruction (WMD), this is still under consideration and not yet a fact. The Department of Homeland Security is considering this classification when certain criteria are met. However, some experts argue that the threat of fentanyl being used as a weapon is a "fringe scenario" and there are other toxic chemicals that could be used instead. The claim that fentanyl is a WMD is therefore not universally accepted and could be seen as potentially misleading. 
https://wenstrup.house.gov/updates/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=406021 
https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2019-04-16/report-dhs-considering-classifying-fentanyl-as-weapon-of-mass-destruction
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While fentanyl is indeed a powerful opioid and can be dangerous in small amounts, classifying it as a weapon of mass destruction (WMD) is not accurate. WMDs typically refer to nuclear, radiological, chemical, biological or other weapons that can cause significant harm on a large scale. Fentanyl, while dangerous, does not fit this definition. The incident with the Florida police officer was unfortunate, but it's important to note that it was an accidental exposure, not a deliberate act of mass destruction. 
https://www.cdc.gov/drugoverdose/opioids/fentanyl.html 
https://www.armscontrol.org/factsheets/wmds 
https://www.npr.org/2018/09/21/650508147/fentanyl-used-to-execution-drugs-leads-to-fight-over-death-penalty-in-nebraska

column5:
The Strategic Petroleum Reserve has been drawn down over 200 million barrels over the past year (~1/3 of the previously stored amount). https://www.eia.gov/dnav/pet/hist/LeafHandler.ashx?n=pet&s=mcsstus1&f=m 
The refill being promoted is to pilot the purchase of up to 3 million barrels in January & deliver in February. https://www.spr.doe.gov/posting/PURCHASE/FY23%20Winter%20Oil%20Purchase%203MMB/1-Request%20for%20Proposal/FY23%20Winter%20Oil%20Purchase%203MMB%20Request%20for%20Proposal.pdf
column8:
The Democrats blocked Republicans from filling the SPR when oil prices were at $24, significantly below current prices.    
https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-09-13/biden-may-buy-oil-just-below-80-democrats-stymied-trump-at-24
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. It's true that the Energy Department is buying back oil at a lower price than it was sold for, which could be seen as a good deal for taxpayers and a way to strengthen energy security (https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-begins-buying-back-oil-strategic-reserve-official-2022-12-16/). However, the claim that this action directly reduced gas prices is misleading. The impact of releasing oil from the SPR on gas prices is not immediate and depends on various factors, including production from the U.S. and OPEC and global relations with Russia (https://www.npr.org/2022/04/03/1090498777/how-releasing-federal-oil-reserves-affects-the-price-at-the-pump). Furthermore, the SPR is an insurance policy for the U.S. economy, and its levels are at their lowest since 1984, raising concerns about energy security (https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-begins-buying-back-oil-strategic-reserve-official-2022-12-16/).
column13:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that the administration plans to purchase oil to refill the SPR at a price lower than the selling price, the impact on domestic fuel prices is not straightforward. Some of the oil released from the SPR to lower domestic fuel prices was exported to Europe and Asia, which may have blunted the intended effect on domestic prices. Furthermore, the administration's decision to refill the SPR is not solely driven by profit motives, but also by the need to maintain strategic reserves and negotiate lower fuel prices. 
https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/oil-us-reserves-head-overseas-gasoline-prices-stay-high-2022-07-05/ 
https://www.politico.com/news/2022/10/18/biden-spr-oil-reserve-release-fuel-prices-00062269
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) was sold at a high price and is being refilled at a lower price, this doesn't necessarily equate to a profit for taxpayers. The SPR is a government-owned reserve meant to provide a buffer against potential disruptions in oil supplies, not a profit-making entity. The money from the sale goes back into the government's general fund, not directly to taxpayers. Furthermore, the price of gas is influenced by a multitude of factors, not just the sale or purchase of oil from the SPR.
https://www.energy.gov/fe/services/petroleum-reserves/strategic-petroleum-reserve 
https://www.eia.gov/energyexplained/oil-and-petroleum-products/prices-and-outlook.php

column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Elon Musk's stance on doxxing policy is consistent with his actions. After buying Twitter, Musk clarified his stance on doxxing, stating that real-time posting of someone's location violates policy, but delayed posting is acceptable. This was in response to an account tracking his private jet in real-time, which he viewed as a personal safety risk. Twitter suspended the account, reinstated it, and then suspended it again for violating its policy on sharing live location information. Musk's son was mistakenly followed due to this account, leading to Musk's decision.

column14: This tweet is potentially misleading. Elon Musk's statement about doxxing policy and the First Amendment is accurate. Real-time posting of someone's location can be considered as doxxing, which is a violation of privacy. However, delayed posting of locations or publishing flight records is protected under the First Amendment, as per the Smith v. Daily Mail Pub. Co. case. This doesn't necessarily mean Musk is being "owned" by his own website, but rather he is clarifying the policy. Here's the link to the case he mentioned: https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/443/97/
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading as it lacks context and specific details about how Elon Musk is supposedly being "owned" by his own website. column5:
Global temperatures have risen by .14 degrees Fahrenheit each decade since 1880. Since 1981, temperatures have risen .32 degrees Fahrenheit each decade, indicating an acceleration in global warming. 
https://www.climate.gov/news-features/understanding-climate/climate-change-global-temperature
column8:
Since 1880, Earth’s temperature has risen by 0.14° Fahrenheit (0.08° Celsius) per decade, but since 1981 the rate of warming is more than twice that: 0.32° F (0.18° C) per decade.  https://www.climate.gov/news-features/understanding-climate/climate-change-global-temperature    Using short time scales for global temperature trends is called "cherry picking."   
https://www.climate.gov/news-features/blogs/beyond-data/duct-tape-and-seesaws-climate-trends-101   
https://skepticalscience.com/3-levels-of-cherry-picking-in-a-single-argument.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that 2022 may not be the warmest year on record due to a rare triple-dip cooling La Niña, this doesn't reverse the long-term warming trend. The 10-year average for 2013-2022 is estimated to be 1.14°C above the pre-industrial baseline, compared to 1.09°C from 2011 to 2020. The last eight years have been unusually warm, exceeding 1.2C above pre-industrial levels. The long-term warming since the industrial revolution is attributable to increased concentrations of CO2 and other greenhouse gases. Looking at data over a short period in isolation can lead to misleading conclusions. The impacts of climate change, such as record ocean heat levels and rising sea levels, are becoming more dramatic. 
https://public.wmo.int/en/media/press-release/eight-warmest-years-record-witness-upsurge-climate-change-impacts 
https://www.carbonbrief.org/factcheck-no-global-warming-has-not-paused-over-the-past-eight-years/
column16: This tweet is misleading. While it's true that the time period from 2015-2022 represents a small fraction of manmade CO2 contribution, it's incorrect to suggest that climate change is a hoax based on this short-term data. Climate change is a long-term trend, and short-term fluctuations do not negate the overall warming trend. The World Meteorological Organization confirms that the past decade was the hottest on record (https://public.wmo.int/en/media/press-release/2020-was-one-of-three-warmest-years-record). Furthermore, NASA's data shows a clear long-term global warming trend (https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/global-temperature/).

column11: This tweet is misleading. The image of the blue owl is actually a doctored photo. The original photo, taken by Knut Eisermann, features a brown owl, not a blue one. The image has been manipulated to give the owl blue feathers and pink eyes. The original watermark has also been cropped out and the image flipped. The claim that this is a "Philippines Blue owl" or an owl from Madagascar is false. The original photo is of a Guatemalan Pygmy-Owl taken in Guatemala. This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that some states have restrictive abortion laws, it's not accurate to say a six-week pregnancy has more rights than women in the listed states. Twenty states prohibit abortions after the fetus achieves viability, between 24 and 28 weeks. Forty-four states prohibit abortions after a specified duration, with exceptions for the health of the woman, fetal abnormalities, or cases of rape or incest. The limits range from six weeks in Texas to the third trimester in Virginia. Furthermore, the majority of Americans believe abortion should be legal in all or most circumstances, and support for legal abortion declines as pregnancy progresses.

He also plans to sell only 2% of his Coinbase holdings over the next year, while still controlling 59.5% of its voting shares. Furthermore, Armstrong has expressed his expectation for the company’s NFT business to be on par with, or even bigger than its cryptocurrency business. Therefore, his selling of shares could be part of a broader strategy rather than a sign of impending doom.

This sale could have been scheduled months in advance and not necessarily indicative of his confidence in Coinbase.

column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Twitter has seen a drop in revenue, it's not solely due to activist groups pressuring advertisers. There are several factors at play, including concerns about content moderation, layoffs, and the resignation of key personnel. Musk's claim that "nothing has changed with content moderation" is contradicted by reports of Twitter shutting off employee access to certain content moderation tools and eliminating its curation team. Furthermore, advertisers have been leaving Twitter since Musk announced his intentions to buy the company, not just due to activist pressure. 
https://techcrunch.com/2022/11/04/musk-blames-activist-groups-for-major-advertisers-pausing-spending-on-twitter/ 
https://www.reuters.com/technology/twitter-start-layoffs-friday-morning-internal-email-2022-11-04/
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading as it juxtaposes two tweets to imply that Elon Musk's rhetoric is similar to that of Donald Trump's. However, the context of the two tweets is different. Musk's tweet is about Twitter's revenue drop due to activist pressure, while the parody Trump tweet is about economic issues due to left-wing pressure. The similarity in structure does not necessarily mean the rhetoric is the same. 
- Musk's tweet: https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1456345785653755904 
- Parody Trump tweet: https://twitter.com/tobymorton/status/1005110621140807680
column16: This tweet is ambiguous and doesn't provide enough context to determine if it's misinformed or potentially misleading. The images attached are not accessible, and without knowing the content of the "rhetoric" the user is referring to, it's impossible to provide a factual analysis. Please provide more information or context.

column5:

https://blog.twitter.com/en_us/topics/product/2021/introducing-birdwatch-a-community-based-approach-to-misinformation
column8: Falsely attributes, by general assumptions, the note added under the WH tweet was done by Twitter and a new consequence linked directly to the change of ownership. It's a Birdwatch note, written by users of  the twitter platform, not by Twitter employees or owners
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that the fact-check may seem negative towards Biden, it's important to note that it's providing context to his claim about job creation. Biden's statement about creating 700,000 manufacturing jobs is numerically correct, but it doesn't account for other factors like the pandemic relief bills that began under Trump and contributed to the rise in manufacturing jobs. Also, the recent job gains still leave manufacturing employment well below historical highs. Therefore, the fact-check isn't necessarily smearing negativity, but rather providing a more nuanced view of the situation. 
https://www.politifact.com/article/2022/nov/01/joe-biden-and-manufacturing-jobs-closer-look/ 
https://www.politico.com/news/2020/09/16/trump-manufacturing-jobs-record-415588
column13:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that media coverage can influence public perception, it's not necessarily a smear campaign against Biden. The negative coverage has increased as Biden's poll numbers have dropped, creating a feedback loop. However, this doesn't mean the media is intentionally trying to smear Biden. It's also important to note that complex issues like inflation and the ongoing COVID-19 crisis are often oversimplified in media narratives, which can contribute to negative perceptions. 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/press-bothsideism-has-failed-biden-and-america/
column14: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that media ownership can influence the information we receive, the fact-check in question is not necessarily a smear on Biden. It's providing context to his statement about job creation. The distinction between regaining lost jobs and creating new ones is important for understanding the full picture of economic recovery. Here's a source that explains the difference: https://www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm It's crucial to have accurate information for informed public discourse.
column16: This tweet is somewhat misleading as it implies that fact-checking is a tool used to smear negativity on political figures, in this case, Biden. Fact-checking is an essential part of journalism and its purpose is to verify the accuracy of information. It's not meant to smear negativity but to ensure the public is informed with accurate information. Here's a link that explains the importance of fact-checking: https://www.americanpressinstitute.org/journalism-essentials/fact-checking/what-fact-checking-how-journalists-do-it/ As for the claim about agencies affecting the deal, without specific details, it's hard to verify or refute.

While it's true that an off-duty Pentagon officer, Eric Welch, was arrested in connection with a drug distribution case, there's no evidence to suggest he was dealing Fentanyl to children during trick or treating. The arrest was made on Oct. 28, not on Halloween, and the charges were related to possession with intent to distribute a controlled substance, not specifically Fentanyl or targeting children. The article may have confused or conflated this case with other unrelated incidents involving Fentanyl. 
https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/local/virginia/off-duty-pentagon-officer-arrested-drug-distribution-case/65-0ecc31f1-32f1-498a-92bf-c86461c2ac07

A search of reputable news outlets, including the New York Times and Washington Post, shows no reports of an off-duty Pentagon cop dealing Fentanyl to children during trick or treating. It's important to verify information before sharing it.
https://www.nytimes.com/ 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/

column5:
2 members of the New Black Panther Party in paramilitary gear stood outside a polling place in Philadelphia in 2008. The DOJ filed a lawsuit but later  dropped the case, prompting the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights to further investigate the circumstances.    
https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203550604574361071968458430    
https://oig.justice.gov/reports/2013/s1303.pdf    
https://www.usccr.gov/files/pubs/NBPH/docs/USCCR_NBPP_report.pdf
column8: Only two Black Panthers — seen in the photo — appeared at one polling location in 2008. However, the original Tweet is correct in that the DOJ tried "to hide the extensive involvement of high-level political officials" in dismissal of a voter intimidation case against the men.    https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/28/AR2010102807129.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The Obama DOJ did not insist that voter intimidation was legal. In fact, the Justice Department filed a civil lawsuit against the New Black Panther Party and its members for voter intimidation. However, the case was dropped against all but one member, King Samir Shabazz, due to lack of prosecutable evidence. The DOJ did obtain an injunction prohibiting Shabazz from displaying a weapon within 100 feet of a polling place until 2012. 
https://www.jacksonville.com/story/news/nation-world/2010/07/29/fact-check-reports-voter-intimidation-appear-exaggerated/15936860007/ 
https://judiciary.house.gov/media/press-releases/smith-calls-for-inspector-general-to-investigate-doj-handling-of-new-black
column13:
This tweet is misleading. The DOJ did not insist it was legal for the Black Panthers to intimidate voters. In fact, they obtained an injunction against the individual who brought a weapon to the polling place. The DOJ makes enforcement decisions based on merits, not race, gender, or ethnicity. Recent incidents of alleged voter intimidation at drop box locations in Arizona have been referred to the DOJ, showing that they take such matters seriously. 
https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2010/07/13/128492601/former-doj-attorney-alleges-racial-motive-in-justice-department-decision 
https://grijalva.house.gov/ahead-of-midterm-election-rep-grijalva-urges-doj-to-protect-arizona-voters-from-voter-intimidation/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The incident referred to happened in 2008, where two members of the New Black Panther Party stood outside a polling station in Philadelphia. The DOJ did file a lawsuit but later narrowed its scope due to lack of evidence of voter intimidation. The claim that Obama's DOJ insisted it was perfectly legal is incorrect. As for the "patriots" observing dropboxes, it's important to note that voter intimidation is illegal under federal law.
https://www.factcheck.org/2010/07/new-black-panther-party/ 
https://www.justice.gov/crt/voting-section 
https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/594

column5:
The "Saudis" did not "partner with Elon Musk to buy Twitter". Rather a single Saudi billionaire - Prince Alwaleed bin Talal au Saud - who owned a large stake in Twitter since 2011, chose to maintain his investment rather than selling it to Elon as part of Twitter's buyout.
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/saudis-kingdom-holding-company-maintain-twitter-stake-2022-10-28/ 
https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/oct/07/saudi-princes-investment-stake-twitter-alwaleed-bin-talal-kingdom-holding
column8:
The below links, the "Saudis" may not have "partnered with Elon Musk to buy Twitter." Rather a Saudi concern has owned a stake since 2011 & doubled it in Oct. 2022. Direct coordination between Saudi holding company and Musk is unclear.
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/saudis-kingdom-holding-company-maintain-twitter-stake-2022-10-28/ 
https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/oct/07/saudi-princes-investment-stake-twitter-alwaleed-bin-talal-kingdom-holding
column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Saudi Arabia sentenced a dual US-Saudi citizen to 16 years in prison for critical tweets, the claim that the Saudis partnered with Elon Musk to buy Twitter is not entirely accurate. Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Holding Company and the private office of Prince Alwaleed Bin Talal have maintained their existing ownership of Twitter shares valued at $1.89 billion after Elon Musk's takeover. They did not buy Twitter with Musk, but rather kept their existing stake. As for the question of promoting free speech, it's worth noting that Saudi Arabia has a history of repressing speech and imprisoning critics. Musk, on the other hand, has expressed a desire for fewer limits on Twitter content. 
https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2022/10/elon-musk-free-speech-absolutist-is-silent-about-his-saudi-partners/ 
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/saudis-kingdom-holding-company-maintain-twitter-stake-2022-10-28/
column13:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While Elon Musk did purchase Twitter, it's not accurate to say that Saudi Arabia partnered with him to buy it. Musk brought on a number of investors, including entities linked to China, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia. The deal is also subject to review and potential reversal by CFIUS. Therefore, the implication that Saudi Arabia bought Twitter to suppress free speech is not substantiated. 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/the-national-security-grounds-for-investigating-musks-twitter-acquisition/
column14:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that a 72-year-old American citizen was sentenced in Saudi Arabia for critical tweets, the claim that Saudi Arabia partnered with Elon Musk to buy Twitter is incorrect. Elon Musk has not announced any such partnership. Furthermore, the screenshot attached is about the roll over of existing shares, not a new purchase. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/saudi-court-sentences-us-citizen-16-years-jail-rights-group-2022-10-18/ 
https://www.cnbc.com/2022/10/28/prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-rolls-twitter-stake-into-private-vehicle.html

Elon Musk took ownership of Twitter, but Saudi Arabia's Kingdom Holding Company and the private office of Prince Alwaleed Bin Talal simply maintained their existing ownership of Twitter shares valued at $1.89 billion. They did not partner with Musk for the takeover. The tweet could potentially mislead readers into thinking that Saudi Arabia has a controlling stake in Twitter, which is not the case. 
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/saudis-kingdom-holding-company-maintain-twitter-stake-2022-10-28/

column11:
This tweet is accurate. Elon Musk did fire Vijaya Gadde, along with other Twitter executives, after accusing them of misleading him and Twitter investors about the number of fake accounts on the platform. Gadde was indeed responsible for major user account decisions, including the decision to permanently ban former President Trump from Twitter. However, it's important to note that Musk's decision to fire Gadde and other executives came after his acquisition of Twitter, and not directly due to Trump's Twitter suspension. 
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/elon-musk-completes-44-bln-acquisition-twitter-2022-10-28/

column15:

Elon Musk did fire Vijaya Gadde, along with other top executives at Twitter, after accusing them of misleading him and Twitter investors over the number of fake accounts on the platform. This occurred after Musk's acquisition of Twitter. However, it's worth noting that Gadde was not solely responsible for Trump's Twitter suspension, as the decision would have been made collectively by Twitter's policy team. 
https://www.reuters.com/markets/deals/elon-musk-completes-44-bln-acquisition-twitter-2022-10-28/ 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/05/09/twitter-lawyer-censor-musk/

However, Twitter's policy on banned users returning is clear - once suspended for severe violations, the user cannot create new accounts. This is outlined in Twitter's policy: https://help.twitter.com/en/rules-and-policies/twitter-rules Without specific context or official confirmation from Twitter, this claim remains speculative.

column8: This is not the Supreme Court Justice fault. New York has one of the strictest gun laws in the country and has continued to defund police after last year events. Killing someone is already a life sentence in most states and illegal so not really sure if another law would help https://nycitylens.com/wp-content/guns/new-york-city-and-its-gun-laws-how-strict-are-they/index.html
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Justice Clarence Thomas authored a ruling that struck down New York's limits on carrying concealed handguns, it's not accurate to directly link this ruling to the tragic shooting of the young mother. The facts indicate that the woman was targeted, but the reasons are still unclear. Furthermore, Mayor Eric Adams has highlighted the issue of illegal guns being too accessible, which is a separate issue from the Supreme Court ruling. 
https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/mother-pushing-stroller-shot-and-killed-upper-east-side/ 
https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/us-supreme-court-strikes-down-new-york-limits-concealed-handguns-2022-06-23/
column16: This tweet is misleading. Clarence Thomas, as a Supreme Court Justice, does not make laws. He interprets the constitutionality of laws. The Supreme Court's decisions can influence how laws are applied, but they do not directly create or enforce laws. The tweet incorrectly attributes the cause of the tragic incident to Justice Thomas. For accurate information on the role of a Supreme Court Justice, refer to: https://www.uscourts.gov/about-federal-courts/educational-resources/about-educational-outreach/activity-resources/about. For information on gun laws in NYC, refer to: https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/services/law-enforcement/gun-laws.page

column5:
In Egbert v Boule, SCOTUS found the 4th amendment claims did not meet the criteria for government civil liability (Bivens Test) and declined to extend new liability to 1st amendment claims. Existing 1A & 4A protections are not impacted. Border zone is defined by 8 CFR 287  
https://twitter.com/mjs_dc/status/1534536335037456386  
https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/bivens_actions  
https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/8/287.1
column8: What the Court is saying is that there are alternative ways for the victim to seek redress (maybe not ideal but they do exist) and if better ways to handle such claims against border patrol officers exist, Congress should be the one to decide that, not unelected judges https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/08/politics/supreme-court-border-patrol-agents/index.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The Supreme Court ruling in question pertains to a specific case where a Border Patrol agent was accused of unlawfully entering a property and using excessive force. The court did not rule that Border Patrol can enter any home without a warrant and assault individuals within 100 miles of the border. Furthermore, Fourth Amendment protections do apply within the 100-mile zone, and individuals have the right to remain silent and not consent to a search. However, Border Patrol agents can set up immigration checkpoints within this zone and ask individuals about their citizenship status. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/06/08/supreme-court-border-patrol-smugglers-inn/ 
https://www.npr.org/2018/09/20/649187775/federal-agents-board-buses-100-miles-from-border-to-ask-are-you-a-u-s-citizen
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The Supreme Court has not ruled that Border Patrol can enter any home without a warrant and assault you within 100 miles of the border. The 100-mile rule allows Border Patrol to operate immigration checkpoints, but it does not permit warrantless home entries or assaults. Federal protections still apply. Please refer to the following sources for accurate information: 
https://www.aclu.org/other/constitution-100-mile-border-zone 
https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/fourth_amendment

column5:

A real story with the same headline appeared on May 16th in LGBTQ Nation: https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2022/05/dog-new-face-online-homophobia/
column8:
This is a real story. But it was not written by Taylor Lorenz nor was it published in The Washington Post. The story was actually published by a different writer on the website LGBTQNation.
https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2022/05/dog-new-face-online-homophobia/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The article attached in the tweet is not real. Taylor Lorenz, the supposed author, denied writing it. The original meme was created as an inside joke by a member of the LGBTQ+ community. The dog's owners are also a gay couple. The fake article likely originated from a meme featuring the real-life dog, Whitney Chewston. Please refer to these sources for more information: 
https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/homophobic-dog-not-too-fond-of-gay-people 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/washington-post-dog-homophobia-article/
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading as it seems to be based on a single article without providing any additional context or sources. While it's true that internet trolls can misuse images for harmful purposes, it's important to note that the interpretation and use of a meme can vary widely among different internet communities. The article itself does not provide enough evidence to definitively label the dachshund as "the new face of online homophobia". For a more comprehensive understanding of the situation, it would be beneficial to look at multiple sources and perspectives. Here are some resources on how memes can be misused and how to respond:
https://www.adl.org/education/resources/tools-and-strategies/memes-and-online-radicalization 
https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/going-beyond-intelligence/201805/how-respond-internet-trolls 
https://www.wired.com/story/how-to-deal-with-internet-trolls/
column16: This tweet is not misinformed or misleading as it doesn't provide any factual information or claim. It seems to be an expression of disbelief or surprise, which is subjective and personal to the user.

column11:

Wade, it's important to note that the vote alignment can change between the initial vote and the final ruling. The draft does not represent a final decision by the Court or the final position of any member. The authenticity of the draft has not been confirmed.
