column5: This is a digital representation of an animal cell, not an actual image nor does it involve a human cell. https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/image-animal-cell/
column8: This is an artist’s representation and not an actual microscopic image.
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. The image is not a direct, detailed image of a human cell, but a 3D rendering of a eukaryotic cell. It was created using X-ray, nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), and cryo-electron microscopy datasets to visualize various cellular processes. The image was created by Evan Ingersoll and Gael McGill for Cell Signaling Technology, Inc., a private biomedical company. It's an attempt to visualize the complexity and beauty of the cell's molecular choreography, not a direct microscopic image. https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/image-animal-cell/
column13:
This tweet is misleading. The image referred to is not an actual photograph of a human cell, but a digitally-rendered model created by artist Russell Kightley for educational purposes. It was not created using radiography, nuclear magnetic resonance, or cryoelectron microscopy, as some might believe. The image is not a neutral 'capture' of a cell's natural state, but an illustration designed to help explain the relationships between various molecules within a cell. 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-animal-cell/fact-check-miscaptioned-image-was-not-created-with-x-ray-nuclear-magnetic-resonance-and-cryo-electron-microscopy-idUSL1N2P91K0 
https://www.aap.com.au/factcheck/human-cell-image-isnt-what-it-seems-when-put-under-the-microscope/
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading without proper context. The level of detail in a cell image depends on the technology used. Electron microscopes can provide highly detailed images, but they can't show live cells. Fluorescence microscopes can show live cells, but with less detail. Without specifying the method used, it's hard to claim this as the "most detailed" image. For more information, check these links:
- Electron microscopy: https://www.fei.com/introduction-to-electron-microscopy/ 
- Fluorescence microscopy: https://www.olympus-lifescience.com/en/microscope-resource/primer/techniques/fluorescence/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The image attached is a popular representation often used to illustrate the complexity of a cell, but it's not an actual microscopic image of a human cell. Real microscopic images of cells are usually less colorful and detailed due to the limitations of microscopy techniques. Here are some examples of real microscopic images of cells: 
https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-019-45374-9/figures/1 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2829122/figure/F1/

column5: This is a screen shot of a real article, though one about UK airlines, including EasyJet, that lifted mask mandates in March. Between March 28 and April 3, EasyJet cancelled 202 flights due to staffing shortages. https://www.cbsnews.com/news/airlines-face-mask-covid-rules-flights-canceled/
column8: This article pre-dates the lifting of the mask mandate in the U.S. This tweet is falsely claiming that the lifting of the U.S. mask mandate gave rise to cases, which would not be possible as the mandate has only been lifted for less than 24 hours now.
column11:
This tweet is accurate. After dropping mask requirements, airlines like EasyJet have experienced staff shortages due to increased COVID-19 cases. This has led to a significant increase in flight cancellations compared to pre-pandemic levels. The staff shortages are not solely due to COVID-19, but also due to a tight labor market and delays in security checks for new and returning staff. The situation serves as a crucial consideration for the U.S. as it contemplates lifting federal airline mask mandates. 
https://jalopnik.com/overseas-airlines-dropped-mask-mandates-now-theyre-bat-1848762415  
https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/hit-by-staff-shortages-airlines-airports-struggle-with-travel-recovery-2022-04-05/
column14: This tweet is potentially misleading as it implies a direct causation between airlines dropping mask requirements and staff shortages due to COVID-19. While it's possible that the two events are related, the tweet doesn't provide enough evidence to establish a direct cause-and-effect relationship. Other factors, such as general staffing issues in the industry or other COVID-19 related issues, could also contribute to staff shortages. Here's the original article for reference: https://www.cbsnews.com/news/airlines-staff-shortages-covid-19-mask-mandates/
column16: This tweet is ambiguous as it doesn't provide any specific information or context. Therefore, it's neither misinformed nor misleading, but it could potentially cause confusion due to its lack of clarity.

column5:
HIPAA applies to healthcare providers and insurers, not professors, so HIPAA has not been violated. However, this action does appear to violate FERPA policies on student health information privacy in educational settings, which were updated in 2020 regarding COVID.    
1. https://www.cdc.gov/phlp/publications/topic/hipaa.html#:~:text=The%20Health%20Insurance%20Portability%20and,the%20patient's%20consent%20or%20knowledge 
2. https://studentprivacy.ed.gov/resources/ferpa-and-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19
column8:
Per HHS, this interaction is not a HIPAA violation. The tweeter goes on to say in a following tweet that they know this isn't actually a HIPAA violation and rather was just being "extra." However, the context may not show for all.  
https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-individuals/guidance-materials-for-consumers/index.html
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Educational institutions are not generally considered HIPAA-covered entities. HIPAA applies to health plans, health care clearinghouses, and health care providers who electronically transmit health data. Therefore, your professor did not break HIPAA by informing the class about your COVID-19 status. However, the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) might apply in this case, which protects the privacy of student education records.
https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/08/31/colleges-want-professors-stay-mum-student-covid-19-cases 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/investigations/2020/08/09/schools-cite-hipaa-hide-coronavirus-numbers-they-cant-do-that/3323986001/
column13:
This tweet is potentially misleading. HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) primarily applies to health insurance companies and health care providers, not individual citizens or most employers, including professors. It's a rule that prevents these entities from sharing certain protected health information without your permission. It doesn't prohibit asking about health information. Misconceptions about the law often stem from people using it as a shorthand for privacy. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/wellness/hipaa-vaccine-covid-privacy-violation/2021/05/22/f5f145ec-b9ad-11eb-a6b1-81296da0339b_story.html 
https://abcnews.go.com/Health/hipaa-violation/story?id=79114788
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) only applies to certain entities like healthcare providers, health plans, and healthcare clearinghouses. It does not apply to individuals such as professors unless they are also healthcare providers involved in your care. However, disclosing someone's health information without their consent can be a violation of privacy rights. Please refer to these links for more information: 
https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-individuals/guidance-materials-for-consumers/index.html 
https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/privacy/laws-regulations/index.html
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading without context. HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) violations typically involve unauthorized disclosure of personal health information. However, without knowing the specifics of what the professor did, it's hard to definitively say if a HIPAA violation occurred. For more information on what constitutes a HIPAA violation, you can visit: https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/privacy/laws-regulations/index.html

column5: 7 minutes after this tweet, FOX posted this: https://www.foxnews.com/media/ukrainian-journalist-oleksandra-kuvshinova-killed-attack

They acknowledged her contributions and expressed their condolences. Here is the link to the Fox News report: https://www.foxnews.com/world/fox-news-cameraman-pierre-zakrzewski-killed-ukraine It's important to verify information before sharing to avoid spreading misinformation.
column16: This tweet is misleading. Fox News did indeed report on the tragic death of their Ukrainian team member, as well as their cameraman. They acknowledged their contributions and expressed their condolences. Here is the link to the Fox News report: https://www.foxnews.com/world/fox-news-crew-member-killed-ukraine It's important to verify information before sharing to avoid spreading misinformation.

column5:
This chart is deceptively formatted, showing only two data points and only a tiny segment of relevant numbers on the y-axis. More complete charts show a very different trend. https://ycharts.com/indicators/us_gas_price 
The president's ability to control gas prices for either good or ill is also minimal. https://money.howstuffworks.com/president-gas-prices.htm
column8:
This graph shows very small changes over a short term period of time. This cherry picked data set may cause confusion about the average trend of gas costs in the United States.     
https://www.eia.gov/dnav/pet/pet_pri_gnd_dcus_nus_w.htm
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While the graph shows a slight decrease in gas prices, it's important to note that since Biden took office, gas prices have risen more than a dollar. The graph's scale also doesn't accurately represent the minor decrease, which is less than 1% of the cost. Furthermore, attributing this small decrease to Biden's actions may be premature, as many factors influencing gas prices are unrelated to his policies. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/12/02/qthis-might-be-worst-defense-biden-administration-yet/
column14: This tweet is potentially misleading as it implies that President Joe Biden is responsible for the gas prices during the specified period. While the President can influence energy policy, gas prices are largely determined by global market forces, including supply and demand, geopolitical events, and natural disasters.
column16: This tweet is not misinformed or misleading, but it is vague. Without context, it's unclear what the DCCC is thanking President Biden for. This could potentially lead to confusion or misinterpretation.

column5:
Rittenhouse was rising from the ground in this image, not kneeling to fire his rifle. Rittenhouse did not ever fire his rifle from a kneeling position on the night in question.    
https://heavy.com/news/kyle-rittenhouse-shooting-video-photos-graphic/
column8:
Except he never kneeled and shot into a crowd, lol. Everyone has seen the videos at this point, no? Why lie about them?     
https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kyle-rittenhouse-jury-video-fatal-shooting-joseph-rosenbaum/
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that intent can be inferred from actions, the law also considers the context and circumstances surrounding the incident. In the case of Kyle Rittenhouse, he was charged with first-degree intentional homicide, but he claims he acted in self-defense. The determination of intent is not as clear-cut as the tweet suggests and is subject to interpretation and evidence presented in court. 
https://www.insideedition.com/christian-crowdfunding-site-raises-over-half-a-million-dollars-for-alleged-kenosha-shooter-kyle
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that intent can be inferred from actions, it's not accurate to say the law is "very clear" on this matter. Intent is often a complex issue in legal cases and is determined based on a variety of factors, not just the act itself. It's ultimately up to the court to interpret the evidence and decide.

column5: This is not a real image of a drone show in Mexico City. It is an edited photograph of a city in Japan with the "drones" added artificially. Original image from photographer Koshi Chiba: https://www.flickr.com/photos/130700920@N08/29707976154/
column8: https://twitter.com/nervatel/status/1455511907989811208?s=21
column11: This tweet is misleading. The image attached is not a genuine photo of drones flying over Mexico City but a piece of digital art. The background of the artwork is actually from a photograph of a mountain in Japan, not Mexico City. The image has been circulating online for at least a year. Please refer to this fact-check for more information: https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/day-of-the-dead-drone-art/
column14: This tweet is potentially misleading. The Day of the Dead is a traditional Mexican holiday, but there's no known tradition involving drones. The image of a sombrero flying over a city might be misinterpreted as a drone, but it's likely just a creative representation.
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The Day of the Dead is a traditional Mexican holiday where families welcome back the souls of their deceased relatives for a brief reunion. It involves various customs and rituals, but drones are not traditionally part of the celebration. The image attached to the tweet could be from a different event or could be an addition to the celebration in recent years. However, without further context, it's hard to determine the exact situation. 
- For more information on the Day of the Dead, you can visit: 
https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/article/day-of-the-dead

column5: “As is common when a defendant claims self-defense, […] the three men cannot be referred to as ‘victims.’”    https://www.foxnews.com/us/kyle-rittenhouse-back-in-court-looters-rioters-self-defense-expert    “‘If more than one of them were engaged in arson, rioting, looting, I'm not going to tell the defense you can't call them that,’ the judge said”    https://abc7chicago.com/kyle-rittenhosue-rittenhouse-trial-kenosha-protest-shooting-police-brutality/11167589/
column8:
https://www.npr.org/2021/10/26/1049458617/kyle-rittenhouse-victims-arsonists-looters-judge-ruled    
It is not uncommon for the term “victim” to be disallowed when one side is claiming self defense. And “looter”/“rioter” can only be used if the defense proves those involved specially did that. The judge also ruled against Kyle in allowing videos they moved to have banned.
column11: This tweet is somewhat misleading. Judge Schroeder has a standing rule against using the term "victim" until a conviction is made, which is why he prohibited its use in this case (https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2021/10/26/kyle-rittenhouse-trial-judge-victims/8557603002/). The tweet also implies that the judge will allow the defense to label the individuals as "rioters, looters or arsonists" without condition. However, the judge stated these terms can only be used if the defense provides evidence supporting such claims (https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/hearing-may-settle-use-of-force-experts-at-rittenhouse-trial/2653952/).
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that the judge in Kyle Rittenhouse's trial ruled that lawyers cannot call the two people he killed "victims," it's not accurate that they can be referred to as "rioters, looters or arsonists" without any restrictions. The judge stated that these terms can only be used if there's evidence to support such claims. The tweet could lead readers to believe that these terms can be used freely, which is not the case.
https://www.npr.org/2021/10/26/1049182941/kyle-rittenhouse-trial-judge-victims 
https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kyle-rittenhouse-trial-judge-rules-lawyers-cant-call-2-men-he-killed-victims/

column5: From the Washington Post fact-checker: "we’re pretty certain a deficit score of zero would only be accomplished with some dubious gimmicks that help disguise the true cost of Biden’s agenda...the president’s claim is misleading.    https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/09/28/bidens-claim-that-his-spending-plan-costs-zero-dollars/
column8:
"Democrats have been desperately trying to pass the $3.5 trillion bill, which the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget has estimated could actually cost over $5 trillion" The bill will be paid for with taxes, so it doesn't cost $0.  
https://www.dailywire.com/news/democrat-senator-deals-death-blow-to-bidens-3-5-trillion-agenda-definition-of-fiscal-insanity
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. It's true that Trump's tax cuts, particularly the reduction in the corporate tax rate, significantly increased the national debt by about $1.9 trillion over 11 years, as per the CBO's estimation (https://www.propublica.org/article/national-debt-trump). However, while President Biden claims his Build Back Better Agenda is fully paid for, it's important to note that this is based on the assumption of increased taxes on large corporations and the super wealthy. Whether this plan will indeed reduce the national debt in the long run remains to be seen (https://www.factcheck.org/2021/08/biden-leaves-misleading-impression-on-u-s-debt/).
column13: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that officials have discussed offsetting infrastructure spending by raising taxes on corporations, the overall price tag of the Build Back Better Agenda could approach $4 trillion, including several tax incentives and temporary tax cuts. This could increase the size of the proposal by hundreds of billions of dollars, which may not be fully covered by the proposed tax increases. Furthermore, pursuing compromise with Republicans and business leaders could require dropping or scaling back plans to raise taxes. https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/22/business/biden-infrastructure-spending.html
column14:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that President Biden's Build Back Better Agenda is designed to be paid for through tax increases on corporations and the wealthy, it's not guaranteed that it will fully cover the cost. The Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget estimates that the plan could add $800 billion to $3.5 trillion to the debt over a decade. Furthermore, the Tax Foundation suggests that the tax increases might not raise as much revenue as expected. 
https://www.crfb.org/blogs/how-much-will-build-back-better-act-cost 
https://www.taxfoundation.org/build-back-better-act-tax-increases/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that President Biden's Build Back Better Agenda is designed to be fully funded, it relies on the assumption that Congress will pass proposed tax increases on corporations and the wealthy. If these tax increases are not passed, the plan may not be fully funded. Furthermore, the cost of the plan may exceed initial estimates, which could also result in it not being fully funded. Supporting URLs:
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/29/biden-says-his-economic-plan-is-paid-for-heres-whats-really-going-on.html 
https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2021/09/28/the-build-back-better-act-is-it-paid-for/

column5: This sort of "reporting" is entirely based on an urban legend and only serves to make parents paranoid of their neighbors. https://www.snopes.com/ap/2017/10/29/warning-marijuana-halloween-candy-derided-scare-tactic/
column8: There is absolutely no factual source that backs the claim this is truly happening. The packages are labeled as edibles and are a stock photo. There are not any instances of this happening recently
column11:
This tweet is accurate. The snacks shown in the images are indeed laced with THC, the main psychoactive compound in cannabis. There have been incidents where children have mistakenly consumed these snacks, leading to hospitalization due to the high THC content. It's important to note that while medical cannabis is legal in some states, it should be kept out of reach of children. The packaging of these products can be misleading, as they resemble popular snacks, which has led to concerns from companies like Frito-Lay. 
https://www.healthline.com/health/cbd-vs-thc 
https://www.latintimes.com/toddler-hospitalized-after-eating-marijuana-laced-snack-looked-cheetos-479853
column12:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Bensalem police confiscated THC-laced snacks that resembled candy, these were not intended for distribution in Halloween bags but were bought in California for sale in Pennsylvania. The fear of strangers tampering with Halloween candy is largely an urban myth, with no verified cases in decades of news reports. It's always good to check your child's candy, but the risk is not as high as often portrayed. 
https://6abc.com/bensalem-police-halloween-candy-childrens-safety-child-care/11057472/ 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/23/thc-cyanide-razor-blades-how-sketchy-urban-myths-taught-parents-fear-halloween-candy/
column13:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that parents should be vigilant about their children's Halloween candy, cases of tampered candy are rare and mostly urban legends. It's important to only allow children to eat factory-wrapped treats and discard any with damaged wrappers or without labels. However, the claim that all confiscated snacks are laced with THC may cause unnecessary panic. It's always good practice to check your child's candy, but also remember to keep medications and potential allergens away from children during this time. 
https://blogs.cdc.gov/publichealthmatters/2019/10/halloweentips/ 
https://reviewed.usatoday.com/parenting/features/halloween-safety-tips
column14:
This tweet is accurate in its warning to parents to check their children's Halloween candy. The images attached show snacks that are indeed infused with THC, a psychoactive compound found in cannabis. However, it's important to note that these products are intended for medical use and are distributed in accordance with local state initiatives regarding medical cannabis laws. They are not meant to be given to children. It's always a good practice to inspect any candy or snacks your child receives, not just during Halloween. 
https://www.fda.gov/news-events/public-health-focus/fda-regulation-cannabis-and-cannabis-derived-products-including-cannabidiol-cbd 
https://www.healthychildren.org/English/safety-prevention/at-play/Pages/Halloween-Safety-Tips.aspx

It's important to check children's Halloween candy to ensure their safety. However, it's worth noting that instances of people giving out drug-laced candies on Halloween are extremely rare.

column8:
COVID-19 vaccines do not cause HIV. There is some evidence that Adenovirus type-5 vectored vaccines increase risk of catching HIV in men/AMAB. There are currently no approved vaccines in Australia that are Adenovirus-5 vectored vaccines.

column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While some early COVID-19 vaccine candidates raised concerns about increased susceptibility to HIV, these were specific to vaccines using the Ad5 vector. Leading vaccines like those from Johnson & Johnson and AstraZeneca use different adenoviruses as vectors and there's no evidence that these increase the risk of HIV infection. HIV is primarily transmitted through certain bodily fluids and mother-to-child transmission, not vaccinations. The testing mentioned in the screenshot could be a precautionary measure rather than a direct result of vaccination. 
https://www.science.org/content/article/could-certain-covid-19-vaccines-leave-people-more-vulnerable-aids-virus 
https://www.healthline.com/health/false-positive-hiv-test
column13:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While some research suggests that certain COVID-19 vaccine candidates could increase susceptibility to HIV, it's important to note that this is not a confirmed effect and is specific to certain types of vaccines, not all. For instance, there's no evidence that adenoviruses used in vaccines by Johnson & Johnson and AstraZeneca increase the risks of an HIV infection. Furthermore, overall data does not support the notion that vaccines adversely affect the health of HIV patients or accelerate disease progression. Vaccines are generally recommended for HIV patients as they are most effective before the onset of significant immunosuppression. 
https://www.science.org/content/article/could-certain-covid-19-vaccines-leave-people-more-vulnerable-aids-virus 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4117268/
column14:
This tweet is misleading. The COVID-19 vaccines do not cause HIV. The HIV testing mentioned in the screenshot is likely due to standard medical procedures when a patient presents with a fever of unknown origin, not because of the vaccine. The World Health Organization and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have both confirmed that COVID-19 vaccines do not cause HIV. 
https://www.who.int/news-room/feature-stories/detail/mythbusters 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/facts.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Vaccines, including COVID-19 vaccines, do not cause HIV. Vaccines work by stimulating our immune system to produce an immune response, but they do not cause the diseases they protect against. Here are some reliable sources for further reading:

The urgency of the fight to protect abortion access is subjective and depends on one's perspective, but recent legislative actions, such as the passing of restrictive abortion laws in Texas, could be seen as making this fight more urgent.

column11: This tweet is misleading. Gov. DeSantis did speak with FEMA Director Deanne Criswell and declared a state of emergency in Miami-Dade County, which allowed President Biden to approve federal emergency aid from FEMA. This happened on Thursday, before the tweet was posted. FEMA was indeed ready to deploy and support the recovery effort. The governor also acknowledged FEMA's support on Friday morning. https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-miami-area-condo-collapse/2021/06/25/1010263880/miami-dade-will-receive-aid-from-fema-for-condo-disaster-desantis-says
column14:
This tweet is misleading. According to FEMA's official website, the agency can only be deployed after a state's governor requests federal assistance. It's not a matter of permission from the governor, but rather a formal process that must be followed. Furthermore, Gov. DeSantis declared a state of emergency on the same day of the condo collapse, which would have allowed for FEMA's involvement.  
https://www.fema.gov/disasters/how-declared 
https://www.flgov.com/2021/06/24/governor-ron-desantis-declares-state-of-emergency-in-response-to-surfside-building-collapse/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. FEMA's deployment is not contingent on the governor's permission. According to FEMA's official website, the agency can be deployed when the President declares a state of emergency, which is often requested by a state's governor. However, the governor's request is not a prerequisite for FEMA's deployment. Furthermore, there's no evidence to suggest that Gov. DeSantis delayed FEMA's response to the condo collapse.
https://www.fema.gov/disasters/how-declared
